WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:04.751 --> 02:06.295
I'm really excited to be here.

02:07.254 --> 02:11.216
We have something really special
to share with you today.

02:11.883 --> 02:15.887
In total, between iMac and PowerBook lines,

02:16.596 --> 02:20.225
we have sold over three million units this year.

02:25.397 --> 02:26.940
Okay. That's it.

02:28.358 --> 02:30.319
Well, maybe there's one more thing.

02:31.194 --> 02:34.197
I'm about to show you
something that's amazing.

02:34.489 --> 02:38.952
Something that no one else in the world
has seen yet.

02:39.286 --> 02:42.581
Now, Jony, myself and a small team

02:43.165 --> 02:47.252
have been working really hard
on a secret project,

02:47.836 --> 02:49.254
which is something I've been known to do

02:49.338 --> 02:50.573
from time to time.

02:51.381 --> 02:54.551
The device I'm about to introduce to you

02:54.634 --> 02:57.804
is gonna revolutionize an entire industry.

02:58.972 --> 03:00.766
It's a music playing device.

03:01.433 --> 03:02.726
Okay.

03:03.101 --> 03:04.895
We'll get to that in a minute.

03:05.437 --> 03:09.775
Because what it represents is
as important as what it is.

03:11.318 --> 03:14.905
It's a tool for the heart.

03:15.906 --> 03:20.077
And when you can touch someone's heart,

03:21.119 --> 03:22.788
that's limitless.

03:24.331 --> 03:27.250
If I do say so myself, it's insanely cool.

03:29.795 --> 03:31.463
It's a music player.

03:32.422 --> 03:38.136
It's a thousand songs in your pocket.

03:43.809 --> 03:45.435
I'd like to introduce you

03:47.312 --> 03:48.814
to the iPod.

04:29.980 --> 04:31.022
Hey, Jobs.

04:31.356 --> 04:33.108
Get up, man. Wake up.

04:35.026 --> 04:36.486
I'm up.

04:40.532 --> 04:41.867
I'm up.

04:47.956 --> 04:49.040
I'm up.

05:03.889 --> 05:04.890
Steve.

05:05.056 --> 05:07.225
- Hey, Daniel.
- Hey, what's going on?

05:07.726 --> 05:09.936
<i>- Are you reading Be Here Now?
- Yeah, it's amazing.</i>

05:10.020 --> 05:11.813
I'm reading that right now.
It's unbelievable.

05:11.897 --> 05:14.149
<i>It's the next level.
Hey, speaking of Be Here,</i>

05:14.232 --> 05:16.234
what happened to you last night?
Where'd you go?

05:16.401 --> 05:18.737
I had to study. I know, I know.

05:18.820 --> 05:21.990
You know, I'm not dismissing
the value of higher education,

05:22.073 --> 05:24.201
I'm just saying it comes
at the expense of experience.

05:24.284 --> 05:26.328
The system can only produce the system.

05:26.411 --> 05:28.413
I don't want to be a part of that.
Neither should you.

05:28.497 --> 05:31.333
I agree with you.
It takes balls to drop out like you did.

05:31.416 --> 05:33.001
That's why you should.

05:33.084 --> 05:35.003
- I mean...
- Steven.

05:36.254 --> 05:37.631
Might I borrow you for a moment?

05:38.381 --> 05:39.841
- I'll see you in, see you later.
- Sure.

05:39.925 --> 05:41.927
Thank you. Thanks.
I hope I'm not interrupting.

05:42.886 --> 05:44.095
What about your classes?

05:44.429 --> 05:45.847
I'm not a student anymore, Jack.

05:45.931 --> 05:47.682
Well, you're here, and you're learning.

05:47.766 --> 05:49.434
Sure sounds like a student to me.

05:49.851 --> 05:51.353
If you want me gone...

05:51.436 --> 05:53.188
Why would I want you gone, Steven?

05:53.688 --> 05:55.023
I'm glad that you're here.

05:55.106 --> 05:56.775
Whether you're paying or not.

05:57.192 --> 05:58.860
Now, you're always carrying
this notebook around.

05:58.944 --> 06:01.404
You obviously fancy yourself as an artist.

06:01.488 --> 06:03.865
Why don't you sit in on some design classes?

06:03.949 --> 06:08.286
No. Well, I like the idea of art, the beauty.
But only in the right context.

06:08.370 --> 06:10.413
Just not as a career.
I don't have the necessary talents.

06:10.497 --> 06:12.582
But aren't you interested in electronics?
What about engineering?

06:12.666 --> 06:16.378
There's a growing market for qualified technicians.
What about that?

06:16.461 --> 06:18.088
I don't want to spend my parents' money

06:18.171 --> 06:19.756
to get a degree and become something

06:19.839 --> 06:21.174
as forgettable as an electrician.

06:21.299 --> 06:24.344
Excuse me, what, a degree
is a waste of time now? So...

06:24.427 --> 06:30.100
For some. For others it offers validation.
Job security.

06:30.642 --> 06:31.977
- Steve...
- I'll see you around.

06:32.811 --> 06:36.523
Steven. To be continued.

06:46.950 --> 06:48.743
What are you working on?

06:50.078 --> 06:53.832
Nothing, really.
It's homework for calligraphy class.

06:55.000 --> 06:56.001
It's beautiful.

06:57.919 --> 06:59.838
Yeah, the teacher's this monk, or something.

07:01.006 --> 07:02.048
A monk?

07:02.299 --> 07:04.259
Yeah. Robert Palladino.

07:04.467 --> 07:06.678
He's totally inspiring.

07:07.887 --> 07:09.514
My name's Julie.

07:17.022 --> 07:18.189
Are you leaving?

07:18.356 --> 07:19.524
Yeah. I have to go.

07:24.195 --> 07:25.447
You want a hit?

07:26.865 --> 07:27.866
Yes.

07:29.659 --> 07:31.036
Yes, I do.

07:33.204 --> 07:34.706
Can I take a couple?

07:34.789 --> 07:36.750
- Sure.
- For my friends.

07:37.083 --> 07:40.712
Well, my friend, and my girlfriend.

07:49.763 --> 07:51.723
It's so beautiful.

07:52.766 --> 07:55.894
Like a window to the world.

07:58.480 --> 08:01.358
What do you think it's like in space?

08:02.400 --> 08:03.485
It's...

08:04.361 --> 08:06.571
beyond understanding.

08:07.864 --> 08:09.115
Yeah.

08:10.825 --> 08:13.328
Who has a baby,

08:14.746 --> 08:17.582
and then just throws it away
like it's nothing?

08:20.460 --> 08:23.004
You talking about your birth parents?

08:23.713 --> 08:26.007
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

08:26.466 --> 08:31.054
That's bad. Yeah.
That's making me really sad. I...

08:31.971 --> 08:35.850
Sorry that my life is ruining your high.

08:36.851 --> 08:38.186
It's okay.

08:41.272 --> 08:43.732
I miss you when you're not around.

08:53.284 --> 08:54.994
I love you, Steve.

08:58.248 --> 08:59.791
I love you.

09:04.379 --> 09:06.965
Space. The endless black deep.

09:07.716 --> 09:10.885
What was it that that guru
used to tell us?

09:18.560 --> 09:20.645
There is no time to waste.

09:21.020 --> 09:22.230
Do you hear that?

09:22.731 --> 09:24.149
What?

09:38.163 --> 09:39.998
There he goes again.

10:00.143 --> 10:04.606
Calligraphy is the artful
and visual expression of communication.

10:04.689 --> 10:06.649
Take Garamond, for example.

10:06.733 --> 10:11.029
A typeface specifically designed
to make the very act of reading

10:11.279 --> 10:12.781
more natural.

10:25.418 --> 10:28.797
Computers are inherently designed
to make your lives easier.

10:28.963 --> 10:32.091
Theoretically there's no limit
to what computers can do.

10:49.651 --> 10:52.320
It is not who you were at birth that matters

10:52.695 --> 10:55.740
but what you do with the time you are given.

10:56.115 --> 10:58.576
The moment of your death is fixed.

10:58.785 --> 11:02.914
Life is but a journey to serenity,
to its completion.

11:15.093 --> 11:17.095
Be as simple as you can be.

11:17.637 --> 11:19.764
You'll be astonished to see how uncomplicated

11:19.848 --> 11:21.975
<i>and happy your life can become.</i>

11:42.871 --> 11:46.332
I don't even know what I'm gonna do
when I go back home.

11:47.542 --> 11:48.835
What about you?

11:49.085 --> 11:52.088
What are you gonna do
when you get back to The Valley?

11:52.255 --> 11:53.506
Steve?

11:54.465 --> 11:56.467
Steve? You okay?

12:07.937 --> 12:12.358
No. No, no! No.
It's still black and white.

12:13.651 --> 12:15.028
People want color.

12:15.320 --> 12:17.238
<i>- Pong didn't have color.
- So?</i>

12:17.322 --> 12:18.865
Let's do something better.

12:18.948 --> 12:20.658
It can't do color.

12:20.742 --> 12:21.784
Says who?

12:22.076 --> 12:24.203
Okay, you refuse to do anything

12:24.287 --> 12:26.331
that vaguely escapes your comfort zone.

12:26.414 --> 12:27.624
You're not even my boss.

12:27.707 --> 12:28.875
Well, I damn sure should be.

12:28.958 --> 12:30.168
Hey, Jobs!

12:31.085 --> 12:32.128
What're you doing, Steve?

12:32.211 --> 12:33.254
He's an idiot.

12:33.504 --> 12:35.673
You know, and half the people around here

12:35.757 --> 12:38.134
don't know how to design shit.

12:40.678 --> 12:43.056
People are complaining about your behavior.

12:43.431 --> 12:45.099
- Okay? And, yeah.
- About mine?

12:45.183 --> 12:47.977
And your odor.

12:48.436 --> 12:49.771
Are you showering like we discussed?

12:49.854 --> 12:50.939
I'm wearing shoes. You asked me

12:51.022 --> 12:52.190
to wear shoes, and I've got them on.

12:52.273 --> 12:53.733
That's not part of the deal, Steve.

12:53.816 --> 12:55.735
You've gotta learn how to work well
with other people.

12:58.696 --> 13:00.239
I'm just trying to do it right, Al.

13:00.323 --> 13:01.532
I know you are.

13:01.616 --> 13:02.700
Then let me.

13:02.784 --> 13:04.369
Listen, Steve!

13:04.953 --> 13:07.372
You're good. You're damn good.

13:08.623 --> 13:09.874
But you're an asshole.

13:12.418 --> 13:13.461
Well, that...

13:13.544 --> 13:14.545
Hey. Let me finish.

13:15.797 --> 13:18.341
I want you here. I really do.

13:20.009 --> 13:21.552
Something's gotta change.

13:24.514 --> 13:26.307
- Give me my own project.
- What?

13:26.391 --> 13:27.892
Give me my own project.

13:28.601 --> 13:30.353
I'll do it on my own.

13:30.436 --> 13:33.606
And I'll make the best damn game
you have ever seen.

13:34.440 --> 13:35.566
You're serious.

13:38.152 --> 13:39.237
Okay, Steve.

13:40.279 --> 13:41.948
I need someone to reprogram a troublesome game.

13:42.031 --> 13:43.199
But I'm on a tight deadline.

13:43.741 --> 13:45.743
So if you can deliver,

13:46.160 --> 13:47.745
we'll pay you up to $5,000.

13:49.789 --> 13:50.924
$5,000?

13:52.834 --> 13:53.835
Okay.

13:54.293 --> 13:58.423
And as for your personal issues,
I think I may have a solution.

14:05.013 --> 14:06.723
So many circuits.

14:28.202 --> 14:30.079
Woz? Hey, it's Steve.

14:44.761 --> 14:46.471
Thanks for saving my ass.

14:48.890 --> 14:53.770
Of course. We're friends.
That's, that's what friends do.

15:00.568 --> 15:03.321
I just can't work for other people.

15:06.991 --> 15:11.746
I guess I need my independence.
If that makes any sense.

15:14.332 --> 15:16.542
That makes perfect sense.

15:21.172 --> 15:23.633
I'm sorry for ruining your Friday night.

15:25.093 --> 15:27.595
Are you kidding me? This is great.

15:28.054 --> 15:30.640
I'd do this for free. I really would.

15:31.766 --> 15:34.519
But just out of curiosity,
how much are we getting paid?

15:36.020 --> 15:37.222
$700.

15:39.565 --> 15:42.276
Some big bucks there.

15:53.663 --> 15:54.747
<i>Shit.</i>

15:55.456 --> 15:57.917
This is good. Really good.

15:58.584 --> 15:59.710
I know.

16:02.337 --> 16:04.298
Four days. You aren't kidding around.

16:04.799 --> 16:08.469
I'll have to show it to Nolan,
but this is, this is good.

16:23.943 --> 16:24.986
Woz?

16:25.069 --> 16:26.487
Hi. Hi.

16:29.031 --> 16:30.158
Woz!

16:30.241 --> 16:32.618
Hi! Yeah, I'm in the living room.

16:32.743 --> 16:34.495
Hey. Good news.

16:35.179 --> 16:36.998
Let me guess, your bosses
liked the video game.

16:37.081 --> 16:38.199
They loved it!

16:39.041 --> 16:41.294
$350... That's not bad.

16:41.377 --> 16:43.254
Not bad? It's great.

16:44.589 --> 16:45.840
What are you working on?

16:46.507 --> 16:48.509
I'm writing jokes for my dial-a-joke machine.

16:48.593 --> 16:51.929
I've got some really good funny Polish jokes,
which work because I'm Polish.

16:52.054 --> 16:53.848
Hang out and tell me
what you think of this one.

16:53.931 --> 16:55.016
Ready? Ready?

16:55.099 --> 16:58.853
<i>What is long, and hard, that a Polish bride
gets on her wedding night?</i>

16:58.936 --> 17:00.688
<i>A new last name.</i>

17:04.775 --> 17:05.859
That's hilarious.

17:05.943 --> 17:07.778
Pretty good, isn't it?

17:07.862 --> 17:10.239
What do you call a beautiful
Polish girl? Lucky.

17:14.868 --> 17:15.869
What's that?

17:21.709 --> 17:25.546
That. Now that is gonna be cool.

17:26.631 --> 17:28.633
It's a computer terminal board
I'm working on.

17:29.383 --> 17:32.303
Hooks up to the TV for the display.

17:34.096 --> 17:36.265
What is it like, a kit?
What do you mean?

17:36.724 --> 17:37.725
Well, well...

17:37.808 --> 17:38.976
The code is still buggy,

17:39.060 --> 17:42.271
but in theory it'll display
whatever you're working on. Like...

17:42.355 --> 17:43.606
Show me.

17:44.065 --> 17:45.691
Show you. Okay.

18:23.980 --> 18:26.732
<i>I don't care if HP didn't like it.
It matters.</i>

18:26.816 --> 18:28.025
<i>Yeah. It's got potential.</i>

18:28.109 --> 18:31.570
<i>No, the Sex Pistols have potential.
This is the wheel.</i>

18:31.654 --> 18:32.863
It's the Industrial Revolution.

18:32.947 --> 18:35.157
No more decks, no more mainframes.

18:35.241 --> 18:36.409
That changes everything.

18:36.492 --> 18:37.576
It's pretty cool, I guess.

18:37.660 --> 18:38.786
- Hi, Charlene. Hello.
- Hey.

18:38.869 --> 18:42.748
Cool. It's profound.
How could you not tell me about this before?

18:42.832 --> 18:45.209
I don't know. I was just working on it for my own.
It, it was a hobby.

18:45.293 --> 18:48.170
Exactly. Exactly. For your own. For you.

18:48.379 --> 18:52.300
It's what you wanted.
It's what your gut, your instinct wanted.

18:52.383 --> 18:55.344
Your big evolved brain
wanted something that didn't exist,

18:55.428 --> 18:58.222
so you just willed it into existence.

18:59.348 --> 19:00.599
It's, what do you call the system?

19:00.683 --> 19:01.726
The operating system?

19:01.851 --> 19:03.894
- The operating, and it just shows you...
- That's what I call it.

19:03.978 --> 19:06.355
Yeah, it's just a real time display
of current operations.

19:06.439 --> 19:09.483
You can see what you're working on
while you're working on it.

19:09.567 --> 19:10.818
Okay. Look...

19:10.901 --> 19:12.028
Don't you get this? This is freedom.

19:12.111 --> 19:15.656
This is freedom to create,
and to do, and to build,

19:15.781 --> 19:17.616
- as artists, as individuals.
- Look, look, look.

19:17.700 --> 19:19.535
But look, you're overreacting.

19:19.618 --> 19:23.414
Even if you were developing this
for freaks like us, and I doubt you are,

19:23.497 --> 19:26.334
nobody wants to buy a computer. Nobody.

19:26.417 --> 19:30.004
How does somebody know what they want
if they've never even seen it?

19:33.716 --> 19:35.092
We're going to Homebrew.

19:36.594 --> 19:38.095
No...

19:39.430 --> 19:41.307
I am not presenting anything at Homebrew.

19:41.390 --> 19:43.184
I'm... No.

19:45.061 --> 19:48.105
Why do people drive so slow?
Get out! Move!

19:48.189 --> 19:50.066
I'm telling you right now,
I've been to Homebrew.

19:50.149 --> 19:52.693
I understand the caliber of people
who speak there.

19:52.777 --> 19:54.236
I'm not one of those people.

19:54.362 --> 19:56.697
- I'm telling you this thing is amazing.
- I'm not...

19:56.781 --> 19:58.366
You're gonna be great, Woz.

19:58.449 --> 20:00.951
Steve, could you do me a favor,
could you just please

20:01.035 --> 20:02.536
slow down a little bit
so that I feel like

20:02.620 --> 20:05.581
there's a chance we might
actually get there alive.

20:05.664 --> 20:08.125
I want to get there first
so we present first.

20:09.794 --> 20:11.045
You know if we're gonna do this thing,

20:11.128 --> 20:12.254
we need to come up with a name.

20:12.380 --> 20:14.006
- Yeah, I know.
- Something catchy. Something...

20:14.131 --> 20:15.257
I've been thinking about it.

20:15.341 --> 20:16.467
electric.

20:16.884 --> 20:19.011
It needs to feel like...
I don't know.

20:19.136 --> 20:21.180
What about Enterprise Computers?

20:21.263 --> 20:22.264
No.

20:22.348 --> 20:23.849
<i>No Star Trek names. I swear.</i>

20:23.933 --> 20:25.142
What about Kirk Enterprises?

20:25.226 --> 20:26.394
I will drive this car
right off this road.

20:26.477 --> 20:27.478
Fine, fine, fine, fine, fine!

20:27.561 --> 20:28.729
I will run the car
right off the road.

20:28.813 --> 20:30.731
Jesus! Calm down! Seriously.

20:30.815 --> 20:32.983
Okay. Nothing Trekkie. Jesus.

20:33.317 --> 20:36.946
It just needs to be, like,
something that people will relate to, you know?

20:37.029 --> 20:38.739
Like, it needs to be something that you see,

20:38.823 --> 20:41.575
and you're just, like,
"Man, I just gotta have it."

20:45.246 --> 20:46.414
Apple.

20:47.331 --> 20:48.624
Excuse me?

20:50.000 --> 20:52.169
- Apple.
- Apple, like the fruit?

20:52.420 --> 20:55.923
The fruit of creation. Apple.
It's simple but sophisticated.

20:56.006 --> 20:58.676
It comes before Atari in the phone book, too.

20:58.759 --> 21:04.014
That is so much better
than Phaser Beam Computers.

21:05.099 --> 21:06.767
It's naming it after a fruit.

21:06.851 --> 21:08.477
Apple. Apple Computer.

21:09.186 --> 21:11.063
But, what about Apple Records?

21:11.522 --> 21:13.274
- Apple Records?
- The Beatles' label, stu...

21:13.357 --> 21:14.775
What, they own the word "apple"?

21:14.859 --> 21:16.026
Why do you always hate The Beatles?

21:16.110 --> 21:17.153
Well, I do not hate The Beatles.

21:17.278 --> 21:18.988
- Yes, you do. You always...
- I do not hate The Beatles.

21:19.071 --> 21:20.990
They're just, they're not Dylan,
and you know that.

21:21.073 --> 21:23.033
Okay, and that's a comparison
that you always make.

21:23.117 --> 21:24.285
Well, I... 'Cause it's obvious.

21:24.368 --> 21:25.536
And I don't think it's fair.

21:26.704 --> 21:28.414
Apple. Really? Apple?

21:29.206 --> 21:31.667
Right, listen. If we come up with
something better, we'll change it.

21:31.750 --> 21:34.545
Let's just go with it
and see if it sticks.

21:43.053 --> 21:47.057
<i>It will display up to 192 memory locations</i>

21:47.141 --> 21:49.477
<i>on the monitor simultaneously.</i>

21:50.102 --> 21:54.607
Allow me to explain because
it's quite fascinating, actually.

21:56.567 --> 21:59.403
The logic board is rather complex,
especially compared to some of

22:00.404 --> 22:02.740
the other boards here,
including of course,

22:03.407 --> 22:05.493
the Altair.

22:07.828 --> 22:09.038
And as you can see...

22:09.455 --> 22:13.209
it's much smaller, and cheaper
to manufacture and build...

22:13.667 --> 22:17.379
which, by using dynamic RAM, I was able...

22:18.756 --> 22:23.260
We were able to shrink
the size of the board substantially.

22:23.344 --> 22:25.262
So, it works with your television?

22:25.346 --> 22:27.097
Yes, yes, yes, yes!

22:27.598 --> 22:31.352
It will work on any television,
or video monitor.

22:31.435 --> 22:35.022
All you need is a radio frequency converter

22:35.856 --> 22:38.901
to display the images from your microprocessor

22:38.984 --> 22:40.986
to your set output device.

22:42.613 --> 22:44.448
And it'll run BASIC.

22:48.035 --> 22:52.289
It will also run BASIC,
which I think could be a great...

22:53.541 --> 22:57.378
So I guess that wraps it up.
Thank you very much for your time.

22:57.628 --> 23:00.839
This was terrific. Fuck.

23:01.632 --> 23:03.133
Tough crowd.

23:05.427 --> 23:06.887
Good evening, gentlemen. I'm Frank.

23:06.971 --> 23:08.013
I'm Lutz.

23:08.097 --> 23:12.142
And we're here with reduced instruction
set computing CPU.

23:19.483 --> 23:22.903
Excuse me. Name is Paul Terrell.

23:25.072 --> 23:26.490
Saw your presentation.

23:26.949 --> 23:27.992
And?

23:28.075 --> 23:29.702
And I'd like to talk business.

23:31.370 --> 23:33.247
- What can I do for you?
- Well...

23:33.330 --> 23:36.584
I own a local computer parts store,
in Mountain View.

23:36.667 --> 23:37.793
The Byte Shop?

23:37.876 --> 23:39.086
You buy computer parts.

23:39.169 --> 23:42.631
Yeah. We sell transistors, boards,
soldering equipment, monitors.

23:42.715 --> 23:44.174
You know, hobbyist types.

23:44.258 --> 23:45.384
Like Radio Shack?

23:46.010 --> 23:47.177
No.

23:47.344 --> 23:51.140
Listen, why don't you stop by
and talk to me some time.

23:51.223 --> 23:53.434
There's my card. Give me a call.

23:54.059 --> 23:55.102
Great.

23:55.185 --> 23:56.478
It was nice meeting you.

23:56.979 --> 23:58.063
Steve Jobs.

23:58.188 --> 23:59.648
Steve Jobs. All right.

24:03.777 --> 24:05.362
Who was that?

24:06.614 --> 24:07.965
It's Paul Terrell.

24:09.742 --> 24:11.118
Who?

24:47.446 --> 24:49.657
So what kind of investment
are we talking about here?

24:49.740 --> 24:53.535
Jesus, Steve.
I said I was interested, not buying.

24:53.619 --> 24:57.081
I know. But you're also
not the only interested party.

24:57.164 --> 24:58.874
- Oh, really? I'm not?
- No.

24:58.957 --> 25:00.000
You're not.

25:00.084 --> 25:01.168
That's interesting.

25:01.251 --> 25:03.379
Because it sure seemed that way
the other night at Homebrew.

25:03.462 --> 25:06.090
You think that's the first stop
that we made?

25:06.882 --> 25:08.300
We've been all over The Valley.

25:08.384 --> 25:11.595
Oh, well, then you already have a retailer.

25:11.929 --> 25:12.930
I got offers.

25:13.013 --> 25:17.351
Look, Paul. My middle name's Paul.
My dad's name is Paul.

25:17.476 --> 25:19.228
Bunch of Pauls. I'm...

25:19.311 --> 25:20.813
I think we're kindred spirits here.

25:21.605 --> 25:24.483
We're both businessmen
that operate from our gut.

25:25.067 --> 25:28.070
And my gut tells me to give you this opportunity.

25:32.074 --> 25:36.704
I'm thinking $400 per machine, for 50 units,
paid at the time of delivery.

25:38.789 --> 25:40.791
$400 for a hundred units,
a third up front.

25:40.874 --> 25:42.000
We're not negotiating.

25:42.084 --> 25:43.127
Yes, we are.

25:45.921 --> 25:51.427
Okay. I'll pay $450 per machine. $450.

25:52.344 --> 25:56.223
On delivery, nothing up front.
I know it's asking a lot, Steve.

25:56.306 --> 25:58.892
But it's a big payoff if you deliver.

25:59.309 --> 26:00.978
When I deliver.

26:04.648 --> 26:07.359
$500 per unit and you've got a deal.

26:10.654 --> 26:13.741
All right. You got 90 days.

26:14.992 --> 26:16.535
I'll have it in 60.

26:22.082 --> 26:24.877
Daniel and I just didn't have room
at our place, so...

26:24.960 --> 26:26.920
No, no. I'm glad you asked.

26:29.673 --> 26:32.426
We could move some things around,
give it a good cleaning.

26:32.509 --> 26:35.262
I could move most of my tools to the shed.

26:35.846 --> 26:37.639
Maybe get you boys a fan
when it gets hot.

26:40.309 --> 26:41.977
What do you think?

26:42.519 --> 26:43.854
It's great, Dad.

26:43.937 --> 26:46.482
Yes. It is. This is perfect.

26:46.565 --> 26:50.235
Good. Well, it'll be good
to see you building something.

26:51.028 --> 26:56.158
Good. Hey, keep it neat.

26:56.867 --> 26:57.951
Inside and out.

26:59.411 --> 27:00.596
Thanks, Mr. J.

27:06.919 --> 27:08.253
We got a shop.

27:08.796 --> 27:10.923
Yes, we do.

27:25.229 --> 27:26.313
How's it going?

27:32.611 --> 27:33.779
<i>And voil√†.</i>

27:35.697 --> 27:39.159
It's gotta be straighter.
These have to be more symmetrical.

27:40.369 --> 27:42.037
We have 60 days to complete 50 of these,

27:42.120 --> 27:43.539
and you're worried about the symmetry?

27:43.622 --> 27:46.041
Steve, nobody cares
about the look of the board.

27:46.124 --> 27:48.085
- I care.
- Well, that's just great.

27:48.335 --> 27:50.754
But we were out of time
the minute you made that stupid promise.

27:53.799 --> 27:54.925
You're right.

27:56.510 --> 27:58.095
Need help.

28:00.180 --> 28:01.223
Woz.

28:02.391 --> 28:03.551
We got a problem.

28:05.477 --> 28:07.896
We got to figure out what to do
with all these employees.

28:09.231 --> 28:10.274
- You know Bill?
- Bill.

28:10.357 --> 28:12.025
- Too long, Woz.
- How are you?

28:12.109 --> 28:13.360
Good to see you. How is everyone?

28:13.443 --> 28:14.570
Oh, this is my friend Daniel Kottke.

28:14.653 --> 28:15.988
Hey. I've heard a lot about you.
How're you doing?

28:16.405 --> 28:19.741
Kottke? Kottke from India, of course.

28:19.825 --> 28:21.201
I've heard a lot about you, too.

28:21.285 --> 28:22.953
Don't touch that.

28:23.245 --> 28:25.914
That's Chris Espinosa.
Kid down the street I was telling you about?

28:25.998 --> 28:28.166
Nice to meet you, fella.
This is gonna be so cool.

28:28.750 --> 28:31.962
Great. I'm so glad that you're excited

28:32.045 --> 28:33.630
about this thing we're doing here.

28:33.714 --> 28:34.840
Can I talk to you for a second?

28:34.923 --> 28:35.966
Yeah.

28:36.049 --> 28:38.719
Excuse me, just please stop.
And go over there.

28:38.802 --> 28:41.138
Just out of the way, over there.

28:46.184 --> 28:50.355
We can't afford to pay three people right now.

28:52.107 --> 28:56.361
We can't afford to pay ourselves,
unless we deliver.

28:57.195 --> 29:00.449
And don't worry about Chris. He's just a kid.
So he just wants to help.

29:02.784 --> 29:03.911
You're just a kid.

29:04.786 --> 29:06.038
Cheese!

29:09.625 --> 29:11.001
Thanks, Mom.

29:11.877 --> 29:13.295
So embarrassing.

30:32.708 --> 30:34.876
- All right.
- As promised.

30:36.169 --> 30:38.005
Nice board.

30:45.637 --> 30:46.847
Where's the rest?

30:47.931 --> 30:50.183
The rest? This is all of them.

30:50.642 --> 30:52.185
I asked for 50 computers.

30:52.269 --> 30:56.023
That's keyboards, cases, monitors,
and power included.

30:56.106 --> 30:57.899
Not just boards.

30:58.316 --> 31:02.612
Just boards? Excuse me? Just boards?
These are state-of-the-art.

31:02.696 --> 31:06.992
The logic boards alone are...
Nobody's making anything like this.

31:07.075 --> 31:09.745
They're, what, how dare you!
How dare you!

31:09.828 --> 31:13.623
I think what my colleague is saying is that...

31:14.541 --> 31:16.835
You're not seeing the possibilities here.

31:16.918 --> 31:20.047
That is indeed one unbelievably
kick ass computer.

31:20.130 --> 31:22.090
Not to the consumer.

31:22.174 --> 31:23.467
Well, then maybe your consumer

31:23.550 --> 31:25.093
should start to learn how to...

31:25.177 --> 31:26.303
How to even work that, don't you think?

31:26.386 --> 31:28.013
Listen, boys.

31:28.430 --> 31:33.060
You sold me on a home computer.
That's a keyboard and monitor.

31:33.143 --> 31:34.686
This is a board.

31:35.187 --> 31:37.064
Now, I'm sure this makes
a very capable starter kit,

31:37.147 --> 31:38.565
but the everyday person,

31:38.648 --> 31:40.692
the kind of person that's not an engineer,

31:40.776 --> 31:42.944
or in a computer club like you,

31:43.028 --> 31:45.405
they're not gonna know
what the hell this is.

31:45.489 --> 31:48.617
The average Joe doesn't want to build
their own computer.

31:48.700 --> 31:50.035
They just want to buy it.

31:50.118 --> 31:52.454
They want to take it out of the box,
plug it in,

31:52.537 --> 31:54.372
and have it work.

31:54.581 --> 31:55.624
Steve.

31:56.875 --> 31:58.794
Are you listening to me?

31:59.252 --> 32:03.507
Yeah. These are your boards.

32:04.674 --> 32:06.384
And they will sell.

32:06.468 --> 32:08.845
I can promise you that.

32:09.846 --> 32:11.640
You saw our demo at Homebrew.

32:11.723 --> 32:13.767
You know what it's capable of
with the right components,

32:13.850 --> 32:17.062
which, by the way, all of which you sell.

32:19.397 --> 32:21.525
So, demo it to the consumer.

32:21.608 --> 32:23.735
And market the components separately.

32:23.860 --> 32:26.029
You show them your keyboards,
and your monitors.

32:26.113 --> 32:27.739
You'll move more inventory that way,

32:27.823 --> 32:29.658
and you'll make a hell
of a lot more cash.

32:31.868 --> 32:33.286
You got me.

32:38.166 --> 32:39.626
All right, Steve.

32:40.335 --> 32:41.503
I'll try to sell them.

32:42.546 --> 32:46.299
But if I don't,
I'm not making another order.

32:46.383 --> 32:48.468
Okay. That's fine.

32:48.552 --> 32:52.055
But I think that you might be really interested
in our second model.

32:52.139 --> 32:53.849
What's the second model?

32:55.100 --> 32:57.144
What are you talking about?

32:58.645 --> 33:00.063
All-in-one.

33:33.180 --> 33:34.681
Can I help you?

33:34.764 --> 33:36.266
Yeah, I'm Rod Holt.

33:37.726 --> 33:40.312
The technician. We talked on the phone.

33:40.687 --> 33:42.981
Of course. It's Rod.

33:46.943 --> 33:48.862
Glad you could stop by.

33:50.197 --> 33:52.115
Welcome to Apple Computer.

33:54.701 --> 33:56.161
All right.

33:58.413 --> 34:01.333
Show me this revolutionary piece of shit.

34:02.000 --> 34:03.376
The Apple II.

34:04.836 --> 34:08.465
It's the first ever all-in-one
personal home computer.

34:09.132 --> 34:10.300
And you called me because?

34:11.801 --> 34:16.097
We need a heat efficient power supply.
In the case.

34:16.505 --> 34:18.641
That's impossible, but don't mind me.

34:18.725 --> 34:20.685
I'm just, you know, an engineer.

34:21.268 --> 34:22.395
What's the wattage?

34:22.478 --> 34:24.773
40 watts. And quiet.

34:25.607 --> 34:27.650
- What the hell do you mean, quiet?
- I mean silent.

34:27.775 --> 34:29.610
There's no such thing.

34:29.985 --> 34:32.405
These things run hot.
They need fans in them.

34:32.489 --> 34:33.822
Those bitches ain't quiet.

34:36.076 --> 34:38.078
That's exactly why we need you.

34:38.911 --> 34:40.455
To redesign it.

34:40.996 --> 34:42.206
Redesign what?

34:42.290 --> 34:44.583
The power supply. From scratch.

34:46.127 --> 34:48.797
It can't have a fan, it can't overheat.

34:49.005 --> 34:52.676
And it needs to fit inside a box this size.

35:03.353 --> 35:06.106
Don't do that. Please, don't do...

35:06.189 --> 35:08.525
Whatever. Do whatever you want.

35:19.202 --> 35:21.037
My rate is $200 a day.

35:21.454 --> 35:23.957
And if I ever think things
aren't working out, I walk.

35:25.375 --> 35:26.668
Are we clear?

35:27.711 --> 35:29.170
We're clear.

35:32.549 --> 35:34.342
We're talking about the future.

35:34.426 --> 35:37.220
We're working in a market
that doesn't even exist yet.

35:37.721 --> 35:39.806
What Intel has done for the microprocessor,

35:40.056 --> 35:42.600
we are gonna do for the home computer.

35:46.604 --> 35:49.190
How can you not know
what I'm talking about?

35:52.360 --> 35:55.780
No, ma'am. But it runs on a TV monitor.

35:57.073 --> 35:59.743
Yes, like a television set. Exactly.

36:00.452 --> 36:04.748
I don't think you understand. It's not a TV.
It's a personal computer.

36:05.373 --> 36:07.667
Okay, do you own a typewriter?

36:08.251 --> 36:11.963
Great. Okay, now do you use it? Perfect.

36:12.088 --> 36:16.509
So imagine combining your typewriter
with your television set.

36:19.220 --> 36:21.181
No. Don't... Wait. Wait!

36:21.264 --> 36:24.100
Wait. Please, sir, don't, don't hang up.

36:25.894 --> 36:29.939
Yes. We are small right now, but we...

36:31.274 --> 36:34.235
How do you know we're working
out of our garage?

36:34.444 --> 36:36.404
Who told you that?

36:42.077 --> 36:43.953
Yes. Yes.

36:44.120 --> 36:46.539
Well, thank you for taking the time.

36:49.125 --> 36:52.545
Yes, sir. Apple Computer.

36:53.797 --> 36:56.883
Apple? Yes, like the fruit.

36:59.302 --> 37:00.637
Who's that?

37:02.472 --> 37:06.142
No. No. All I'm asking is
that you come visit us.

37:06.559 --> 37:09.771
One meeting and I promise
you'll be on board.

37:10.688 --> 37:13.775
Around $50,000 would be my guess.

37:15.610 --> 37:16.945
Hello?

37:24.494 --> 37:26.162
What did they say?

37:48.476 --> 37:50.854
What the hell is the matter with people?

37:51.229 --> 37:52.522
Take it the call went well.

37:54.816 --> 37:58.194
I would say I hope you choke,
but that burrito is gonna kill you either way.

37:58.361 --> 37:59.821
Oh, come on, Steve.

37:59.904 --> 38:01.739
Cool your jets, man.

38:02.240 --> 38:03.324
Excuse you?

38:03.825 --> 38:05.994
Just, you know, you're so stressed, you know?

38:06.077 --> 38:08.037
It's, like, relax for a change.

38:08.413 --> 38:11.541
For a change... Why? Why?
So I can be more like you two assholes?

38:11.624 --> 38:15.128
Hey. I'm studying integrated
circuit design here, man.

38:15.211 --> 38:16.379
Are you?

38:17.839 --> 38:19.007
We each do our part.

38:19.090 --> 38:22.719
Really? Then why do I suddenly feel
like your part is expendable?

38:24.053 --> 38:27.682
Out here smokin' up like we're in India.
Well, wake up! We're not.

38:30.685 --> 38:31.769
What happened to you?

38:32.020 --> 38:33.521
- You used to be...
- What? I used to be what?

38:33.605 --> 38:35.190
- Motivated.
- I am motivated.

38:35.273 --> 38:36.566
Really? Then show me.

38:37.066 --> 38:38.943
This is a business, Daniel.

38:39.277 --> 38:41.863
And I can't help you
if you don't help yourself.

38:43.615 --> 38:46.242
I'm in there making a hundred phone calls.

38:46.326 --> 38:48.870
Rod is slaving away.

38:49.245 --> 38:51.080
The kid always finds something to do,

38:51.164 --> 38:52.415
and God knows Woz pulls his weight.

38:52.499 --> 38:53.541
Thank you.

38:53.625 --> 38:55.084
And that's a whole lot of weight.

38:55.168 --> 38:57.587
That really...
That kind of hurts my feelings.

39:11.142 --> 39:14.270
Is this the right...

39:15.730 --> 39:16.856
Apple Computer?

39:17.815 --> 39:19.400
- Yeah, this is us.
- Yeah.

39:19.484 --> 39:20.610
You expecting something else?

39:22.737 --> 39:26.908
Uh, no. Well, yeah, maybe something
a little less Manson Family.

39:28.368 --> 39:29.702
- It's a startup.
- Yeah.

39:30.036 --> 39:31.496
I'm Mike Markkula.

39:32.497 --> 39:33.998
Steve. Jobs.

39:34.249 --> 39:36.209
Steve. I heard a lot about you.

39:36.417 --> 39:38.836
You spoke to Don Valentine on the phone.

39:38.920 --> 39:40.588
He and I are old colleagues of sorts.

39:41.089 --> 39:42.882
The VC from Atari.

39:43.007 --> 39:45.802
Yeah, Valentine.
He said you called him 150 times.

39:45.885 --> 39:47.220
Jesus.

39:47.303 --> 39:50.223
He practically begged me to come
and look at your outfit here.

39:50.306 --> 39:51.724
Called in a personal favor.

39:52.559 --> 39:53.643
Well, Mark.

39:53.726 --> 39:54.811
Mike.

39:54.894 --> 39:56.354
Mike.

39:58.189 --> 39:59.649
Welcome to Apple Computer.

40:00.358 --> 40:02.652
Thank you. Yeah, is this...

40:03.486 --> 40:04.487
This is everything?

40:04.571 --> 40:05.822
- Yes.
- No.

40:05.905 --> 40:08.283
No. We're, we're in six stores
in the greater area.

40:08.783 --> 40:11.327
We'll be launching the Apple II
in about a month.

40:11.411 --> 40:13.413
- In a few months.
- It's close.

40:13.496 --> 40:16.666
Gentlemen, is there some place we can talk?

40:21.671 --> 40:23.089
Here you are, fellas.

40:23.590 --> 40:24.757
For you.

40:25.925 --> 40:29.304
Steve's a fruitarian.
He will only eat fruit.

40:30.471 --> 40:33.433
Okay, boys. I'll leave you to your business.

40:33.516 --> 40:34.559
Thank you.

40:34.684 --> 40:36.311
- Thanks, Mom.
- Thanks, Mrs. J.

40:36.394 --> 40:37.645
You're the best.

40:37.729 --> 40:41.065
Yeah. So where were we?

40:41.149 --> 40:45.028
I'm sorry, don't take this the wrong way,
but what's your angle?

40:46.237 --> 40:47.780
What my colleague is trying to say is...

40:47.864 --> 40:49.198
Where was your last employment?

40:54.037 --> 40:55.079
Intel.

40:58.207 --> 40:59.626
So how much are we talking about here?

40:59.792 --> 41:01.628
- What, the investment?
- That's what you came here for.

41:01.711 --> 41:03.838
Foreplay is not Steve's strong suit.

41:03.921 --> 41:05.131
Isn't it?

41:06.215 --> 41:07.634
Yeah, well,

41:09.427 --> 41:13.556
I've been looking for something
to really sink my teeth into.

41:21.439 --> 41:24.067
Look, Steve. I'm willing to take the risk.

41:24.651 --> 41:27.070
And, this certainly qualifies.

41:27.362 --> 41:29.238
But risk disguised as promise.

41:29.405 --> 41:31.616
And you've shown promise.
I've seen it in your eye,

41:31.741 --> 41:33.910
and I know that look
because I've had it myself.

41:35.244 --> 41:37.205
Tells me you're on to something big.

41:45.088 --> 41:46.923
Yeah. Okay. To the point.

41:47.090 --> 41:48.925
I think we should start
with around 90 grand,

41:49.008 --> 41:51.094
see where that takes us.

41:52.595 --> 41:55.556
Okay, I'm sorry. Could you repeat that?

41:55.640 --> 41:56.933
I'm sorry.

41:57.600 --> 41:59.394
$90,000 isn't gonna get it done.

42:00.177 --> 42:01.646
Wait. Steve, one second.

42:01.771 --> 42:03.981
I don't see anybody else
coming in your garage with a checkbook.

42:04.107 --> 42:05.274
Oh, no, no.

42:05.358 --> 42:07.777
Ninety grand gets it done for us.

42:07.860 --> 42:10.196
I just don't think it gets it done for you.

42:11.364 --> 42:13.616
We'll do the $90,000 investment.

42:13.700 --> 42:15.910
At a $300,000 valuation.

42:15.993 --> 42:18.454
But I also want you to kick
in a $250,000 credit line

42:18.538 --> 42:20.873
with 10% interest to be paid back in full

42:20.957 --> 42:23.626
once we meet net revenue positive.

42:32.969 --> 42:34.137
Okay.

42:38.516 --> 42:39.767
What I mean is, okay.

42:42.103 --> 42:43.187
Yeah.

42:45.314 --> 42:47.400
Now, the first thing you need to do

42:47.483 --> 42:51.487
is incorporate, so that you two as owners
can protect your interest.

42:53.197 --> 42:56.451
And that is, of course,
if you'll have me aboard.

42:58.536 --> 42:59.829
Thank you very much, Mr. Markkula.

42:59.912 --> 43:01.706
Of course. Mike. Yeah.

43:01.831 --> 43:02.999
- How're you doing?
- Yeah, put her there.

43:03.082 --> 43:04.333
- Bill.
- Bill?

43:04.417 --> 43:05.418
- Fernandez.
- Yeah.

43:05.501 --> 43:07.003
- Oh, thanks, Mike.
- Yeah.

43:07.086 --> 43:09.130
Steve. Here's to you, pal.

43:20.475 --> 43:22.393
<i>Are you even listening to me?</i>

43:23.019 --> 43:24.645
I'm pregnant.

43:27.857 --> 43:29.442
Steve, you have to talk to me.

43:31.235 --> 43:33.529
This is your responsibility, too.

43:36.240 --> 43:37.867
Don't you dare

43:38.618 --> 43:39.869
blame this on me.

43:42.747 --> 43:43.840
I'm not.

43:45.875 --> 43:49.212
We both had our moments of...

43:49.754 --> 43:51.255
What? What the hell are you talking about?

43:51.380 --> 43:52.548
You.

43:52.799 --> 43:58.763
When I was in India,
you were with, you know.

43:59.096 --> 44:01.766
Steve? Are you crazy?
You cannot put this all on me.

44:01.849 --> 44:05.311
You can't do this to me right now.
Not now.

44:05.728 --> 44:08.064
Well, I'm sorry this isn't part of your plan.

44:08.147 --> 44:10.483
I'm sorry you have a problem.

44:11.943 --> 44:13.611
But it's not happening to me.

44:14.070 --> 44:16.239
- But this is your...
- No!

44:19.408 --> 44:20.451
Get out of my house.

44:20.743 --> 44:21.953
- What?
- Now!

44:25.790 --> 44:27.583
Oh, Jesus. Here we go.

44:37.343 --> 44:39.971
Hey. Is everything okay out here?

44:40.763 --> 44:43.641
Steven, he's kicking me out.

44:45.768 --> 44:47.937
He doesn't want anything to do with me.

44:52.316 --> 44:54.610
Maybe it's for the best.

44:54.694 --> 44:57.947
You don't deserve to be treated
the way he treats you.

44:58.114 --> 44:59.949
I'm pregnant, Daniel.

45:00.825 --> 45:02.076
What? You're...

45:03.536 --> 45:06.038
He says it's not his,
but I would never...

45:10.376 --> 45:11.919
What did I do wrong?

45:16.757 --> 45:18.009
You didn't do anything wrong.

45:19.927 --> 45:21.178
It's Steve.

45:22.179 --> 45:23.806
That's just him.

45:27.852 --> 45:29.186
He changed.

46:49.183 --> 46:51.769
Hook them right to your television.

46:59.276 --> 47:00.987
His, yeah.

47:07.410 --> 47:09.704
What do you think, J? Ready?

47:23.300 --> 47:26.095
Ladies and gentlemen,
my name is Steve Jobs.

47:27.138 --> 47:28.973
When I founded this company,

47:29.432 --> 47:31.225
I had one goal in mind.

47:31.809 --> 47:35.187
And that was to do what nobody else
considered possible.

47:35.896 --> 47:38.232
To put the power and the beauty

47:38.315 --> 47:40.609
of the world's most advanced technology

47:41.068 --> 47:44.613
in the hands and homes of people
just like you and me.

47:45.448 --> 47:48.409
And I can promise you that after today,

47:49.285 --> 47:52.038
you will never look at computers
the same way again.

47:53.205 --> 47:57.293
So I am proud to introduce to you,
and the world,

47:57.960 --> 48:00.588
the future of personal computing.

48:01.422 --> 48:03.924
The revolutionary Apple II.

49:25.965 --> 49:30.010
Gotta just start over.
It has to be intuitive.

49:30.678 --> 49:33.973
Precognitive. I mean,
I want it to know what you want to do

49:34.056 --> 49:35.891
before you even know
you want to do it.

49:36.016 --> 49:37.810
Wait, are we still talking
about the command prompts?

49:37.893 --> 49:41.230
Bill, we're talking about everything.
The whole thing.

49:41.856 --> 49:45.734
Lisa. Guys, it's the future.
I'm telling you right now.

49:45.818 --> 49:49.697
I mean, Lisa's gonna do for the next 10 years

49:49.780 --> 49:51.824
what the Apple II did for the last three.

49:52.241 --> 49:54.076
I can tell you that right now.

49:54.660 --> 49:56.912
Do you know why people buy an Apple?

49:57.329 --> 49:59.748
Why do they buy an Apple,
not the competitor?

50:01.584 --> 50:03.085
Because it's got bravado.

50:03.752 --> 50:05.504
It's social status.

50:05.588 --> 50:07.006
No, you know what?
It's even more than that.

50:07.089 --> 50:08.424
It's social currency.

50:09.091 --> 50:10.676
We've raised the bar.

50:11.051 --> 50:16.515
And if we want to stay there,
we gotta risk everything.

50:17.600 --> 50:22.938
Great artists, Dylan, Picasso, Newton,
they risk failure.

50:23.606 --> 50:27.234
And if we want to be great,
we've gotta risk it, too.

50:27.735 --> 50:28.819
On the command bar?

50:28.903 --> 50:29.945
On everything.

50:29.987 --> 50:32.156
- What...
- And it starts with the little things.

50:32.239 --> 50:33.866
There's over 20 different functions

50:33.949 --> 50:36.327
tied to every single variation
of the command bar,

50:36.410 --> 50:38.495
which by the way, takes weeks to program.

50:38.579 --> 50:41.790
We're not doing anything that IBM's
not already doing.

50:42.708 --> 50:45.461
And I would rather gamble on our vision

50:45.961 --> 50:48.714
than make a me-too product.

50:48.797 --> 50:52.843
We got to make the small things
just unforgettable.

50:53.344 --> 50:55.596
Let's just start with something simple.
LisaWrite.

50:55.679 --> 50:58.474
What happens if I click
on one of these tabs?

50:58.557 --> 51:01.143
You get a drop-down menu,
and then there's preferences,

51:01.227 --> 51:02.436
and page options.

51:02.519 --> 51:04.063
Okay. Exactly.

51:04.897 --> 51:09.610
Now, which tab do I click on
to get different font styles?

51:14.031 --> 51:19.161
How many custom typefaces
are there on LisaWrite?

51:20.496 --> 51:23.123
That's actually something that I wanted
to talk to you about, Steve, is...

51:23.207 --> 51:25.167
I've been asking for the fonts for months.

51:25.251 --> 51:27.461
But everything we're talking about is conceptual.

51:27.544 --> 51:32.383
And I'm sorry, but typeface,
it isn't exactly a pressing issue right now.

51:34.385 --> 51:37.846
Everything is a pressing issue.

51:39.014 --> 51:42.851
If we want to make
the vision for Lisa a reality,

51:43.852 --> 51:47.189
we gotta put in the hours
and make something great.

51:47.273 --> 51:50.317
Yeah, but we have a hard date
on this software,

51:50.401 --> 51:53.237
and I'm sorry, but adding pretty fonts
is not gonna change that.

51:54.780 --> 51:55.906
Well, Bill?

51:57.366 --> 52:00.953
If you don't share our enthusiasm,

52:01.704 --> 52:05.499
and care for the vision of this company...

52:05.582 --> 52:07.293
No, no, no, no.
I just, I'm not understanding...

52:07.376 --> 52:08.752
- Get out.
- What?

52:10.212 --> 52:12.256
- Get your shit and get out.
- What, wait...

52:12.339 --> 52:13.799
- You're done.
- What, you...

52:13.882 --> 52:15.134
What, are you gonna,
you're gonna fire me?

52:15.217 --> 52:16.343
No!

52:16.427 --> 52:18.429
I already fired you!

52:19.930 --> 52:21.974
Why are you still here?

52:29.773 --> 52:32.234
Steve, he was our best programmer
in the division.

52:32.318 --> 52:35.821
He's the best programmer
that doesn't care about our vision.

52:36.864 --> 52:38.782
Okay. Look, I know it's not my place
to say it, but...

52:38.866 --> 52:40.492
Then shut the hell up, Bill!

52:40.743 --> 52:41.785
Yeah.

52:42.328 --> 52:44.330
So sorry to interrupt you, Mr. Jobs,

52:44.413 --> 52:47.041
but your attorney is here for your 8:00.

52:47.750 --> 52:49.126
All right.

52:51.045 --> 52:53.589
I want to see samples this afternoon.

52:53.672 --> 52:58.969
Somehow we managed to design a word processor
that doesn't have fonts.

52:59.720 --> 53:02.097
And it can't happen again.

53:03.474 --> 53:05.184
So fix it!

53:19.073 --> 53:22.201
2:00 to 3:00. And your 10:00 is waiting for you.

53:25.788 --> 53:27.498
Steve. Steve, hey.

53:27.998 --> 53:29.958
Daniel. Hey.

53:30.042 --> 53:32.336
Do you have a second to talk?

53:35.047 --> 53:37.049
I thought we rescheduled.

53:37.466 --> 53:39.343
It'll only take a second.

53:40.177 --> 53:41.595
That's what everyone says.

53:41.678 --> 53:42.763
Steve.

53:48.602 --> 53:49.812
Fine.

53:50.979 --> 53:54.608
I don't have a lunch, so,
meet me at Good Earth at noon.

53:55.317 --> 53:56.902
- Okay. Cool.
- Okay.

53:57.611 --> 53:58.821
What are you working on these days?

54:00.781 --> 54:02.950
Apple II Plus repairs, mainly.

54:04.368 --> 54:05.536
Right.

54:13.627 --> 54:14.920
<i>I need you to sign this.</i>

54:15.003 --> 54:16.505
<i>It legally preserves your visitation rights.</i>

54:16.588 --> 54:20.968
<i>I don't want them.
Lisa Brennan is not my child.</i>

54:21.552 --> 54:23.137
<i>The courts disagree.</i>

54:23.220 --> 54:27.433
Chris-Ann is a lunatic. It's impossible.
At the very least, improbable.

54:27.516 --> 54:28.767
You knew going into this

54:28.851 --> 54:31.854
the paternity test could prove
that you were the father.

54:32.563 --> 54:34.314
There are 24 million people in California.

54:34.398 --> 54:36.108
That test has a five percent margin of error.

54:36.191 --> 54:39.528
That's 1.2 million people
that could be the father of that child.

54:39.611 --> 54:41.488
It's not me.

54:43.198 --> 54:47.244
You don't need to convince me.
But you do need to sign this.

54:47.828 --> 54:50.622
Miss Brennan is entitled
to your child support

54:50.706 --> 54:53.500
regardless of whether you sign it or not.

54:53.792 --> 54:57.045
Do you really want to give up
the rights to see your...

54:57.129 --> 54:59.840
To see her child in the future?

54:59.923 --> 55:01.800
I don't have time.

55:02.384 --> 55:03.427
Not now.

55:03.510 --> 55:06.972
Steven, as a father,
I implore you to sign this.

55:07.598 --> 55:10.809
Regardless of whether you think
Lisa is your daughter or not.

55:11.477 --> 55:13.562
There's no risk in signing.

55:14.021 --> 55:16.565
Only the regret if you don't.

55:26.742 --> 55:29.661
<i>Frederick Rodney Holt, he recently made</i>

55:29.953 --> 55:32.080
an additional preferred purchase

55:32.164 --> 55:36.919
