55:37.419 --> 55:39.129
Right, and to be clear, this new purchase,

55:39.213 --> 55:41.089
it does not affect Mr. Holt's entitlement to

55:41.507 --> 55:42.925
founder stock.

55:43.008 --> 55:44.843
No, not at all. Steve?

55:44.927 --> 55:47.054
No, no, no. Rod gets his due.

55:47.930 --> 55:48.972
Daniel Kottke,

55:49.056 --> 55:53.185
<i>engineering technician, founding employee.
Now, at our last meeting I,</i>

55:53.852 --> 55:55.771
I don't believe that we met a consensus

55:55.854 --> 55:59.650
as to Mr. Kottke's entitlement
to founder stock.

56:00.692 --> 56:02.903
Well, in all honesty, to be rewarding Daniel

56:02.986 --> 56:05.155
with the same amount of stock as Rod seems

56:05.239 --> 56:07.407
a bit unfair. Doesn't it?

56:08.909 --> 56:11.495
Yes. Daniel gets nothing.

56:11.995 --> 56:13.080
Nothing?

56:13.622 --> 56:14.706
Don't you think you should

56:14.790 --> 56:16.833
think about what you're doing,
for a second?

56:17.125 --> 56:20.295
I have thought about it.
Daniel gets nothing.

56:21.255 --> 56:22.339
Yes, sir.

56:22.422 --> 56:23.882
It's noted.

56:24.967 --> 56:26.343
What?

56:26.718 --> 56:29.388
Any low grade technician
could do his job.

56:29.471 --> 56:32.432
I've been feeding him for years.
It's not personal.

56:32.516 --> 56:34.893
Don't give me that bullshit, Steve.
Of course it's personal.

56:34.977 --> 56:36.186
He can barely do his job.

56:36.270 --> 56:37.479
If we give Daniel preferred stock,

56:37.563 --> 56:40.399
some engineer with 10 times his talent
gets nothing.

56:40.482 --> 56:41.567
Then what happens?

56:41.650 --> 56:43.694
Then we just draw this line
right here, right now, okay?

56:43.777 --> 56:45.862
So you, what are you talking about?
Management, or...

56:45.946 --> 56:47.239
Management and engineers.

56:47.322 --> 56:48.323
Yeah, this means...

56:48.407 --> 56:50.492
I know what it means, Mike.

56:50.951 --> 56:52.160
Thanks.

56:53.537 --> 56:55.789
- No, he's...
- You know what, I don't...

56:57.207 --> 56:59.084
Okay then. Shall we continue?

57:00.127 --> 57:01.712
<i>We can assume that Bill Fernandez,</i>

57:01.795 --> 57:03.088
Randy Wiggington

57:03.171 --> 57:04.965
and Chris Espinosa will not

57:05.048 --> 57:06.425
<i>be receiving</i>

57:06.508 --> 57:08.051
any options?

57:30.741 --> 57:32.200
Drinking a beer, huh?

57:35.370 --> 57:36.788
Tomorrow's a big day for you.

57:38.040 --> 57:39.416
For us.

57:40.417 --> 57:41.710
For us.

57:43.712 --> 57:48.258
Mike told me about what happened
with Bill and Dan

57:49.635 --> 57:54.431
and Chris. And, Steve...

57:56.475 --> 57:57.684
Why'd you do it?

57:57.934 --> 58:00.187
The company outgrew them.

58:00.270 --> 58:03.106
They're not management.
They're not project leads.

58:03.815 --> 58:05.400
It's not my job to be nice to people.

58:05.484 --> 58:07.069
It's my job to make them better.

58:07.486 --> 58:08.862
They don't deserve it.

58:08.945 --> 58:10.822
Then who the hell does?

58:10.906 --> 58:12.157
Do you know how this company works?

58:12.949 --> 58:14.159
Do you want to know?

58:14.284 --> 58:16.912
I'd be happy to teach you,
if you want to know.

58:19.081 --> 58:22.250
Do you know why I started this company with you?

58:23.418 --> 58:27.506
Why I left the safety of HP for this?

58:27.589 --> 58:30.300
I doubt you do. You never asked.

58:32.427 --> 58:34.638
I left because this was my thing.

58:35.097 --> 58:37.599
And you guys thought it was cool.

58:38.266 --> 58:40.852
I just wanted to be one of the guys.

58:43.605 --> 58:48.777
And of all the guys I knew,
you were the coolest.

58:49.986 --> 58:52.447
You were smart, quick-witted.

58:53.532 --> 58:56.451
And this was my chance
to do what I loved.

58:57.953 --> 59:00.288
And to do it for fun.

59:02.207 --> 59:04.626
That's all, that's all I ever wanted.

59:05.711 --> 59:08.004
I thought that's what you wanted, too.

59:12.134 --> 59:14.636
Something's happened to you, Steve.

59:16.054 --> 59:17.723
I'm grown up, Woz.

59:19.891 --> 59:23.145
No. No, you're not.

59:50.797 --> 59:52.883
<i>And now, turning to big news in business,</i>

59:52.966 --> 59:55.802
<i>Apple Incorporated is making headlines
once again.</i>

59:55.886 --> 59:57.512
<i>On Wall Street the tech titan Apple</i>

59:57.596 --> 01:00:00.098
<i>went public this morning,
to incredible market interest,</i>

01:00:00.182 --> 01:00:03.268
<i>as four point six million shares
of its IPO</i>

01:00:03.351 --> 01:00:05.395
<i>were sold within an hour
of the opening bell.</i>

01:00:05.729 --> 01:00:07.856
<i>Wall Street executives had forecast the big day</i>

01:00:07.939 --> 01:00:09.441
<i>for the growing technology company,</i>

01:00:09.524 --> 01:00:11.443
<i>but experts now say Apple's day</i>

01:00:11.526 --> 01:00:13.361
<i>exceeded the market's wildest expectations.</i>

01:00:13.695 --> 01:00:15.030
<i>It was the most over...</i>

